<section xml:id="sec-1-1-General_Counting_Principle" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>General Counting Principle</title>
    <p>This lesson is the first of five lessons on the counting techniques needed for a study of probability. The <em>General Counting Principle</em>, also known as the <alert>Multiplication Principle</alert>, is the foundation for the lessons in <xref ref="sec-1-2-Binary_Counting" text="title"/> and Permutations – Parts <xref ref="sec-1-3-Permutations">I</xref> and <xref ref="sec-1-4-Permutations_II">II</xref>. It can be done fairly quickly, as students generally don’t appreciate the technique’s power until dealing with <xref ref="sec-2-5-Binomial_Probabilities" text="title"/> and <em>Permutations</em>. It is however, an important foundational technique that should be referred to in these future topics.</p>

    <p>The key is to get students to realize that in a two-step process, the list of possible outcomes forms a two-dimensional grid.</p>
        
